    "publishDate": "20 May 2024",
    "excerpt": "Drawing up a Will is essential, but have you considered a Lasting Power of Attorney (LPA)? A real-life case study on estate planning.",
    "content": "HE WANTS A WILL; HE NEEDS A LPA\n\nDrawing up a Will is essential, but have you considered a Lasting Power of Attorney (LPA)? A LPA might be more suitable in situations like the one below.\n\nMany people are familiar with drawing up a Will when planning for the future. A Will is a document that ensures their assets are distributed according to their wishes after they pass away. However, another legal tool that is often overlooked but can be just as important is a Lasting Power of Attorney (LPA).\n\nWhile a Will takes effect after death, a Lasting Power of Attorney (LPA) allows someone to decide on your behalf. At the same time, you are still alive but cannot do so yourself.\n\nWe will dive into a real-life case and explore the importance of considering a Lasting Power of Attorney (LPA) alongside a Will and why the LPA may be the right choice for you and your loved ones.\n\nOur client was diagnosed with stage four cancer and was predicted only to have six months left to live. He wanted to draw up a Will before he became mentally incapable of doing so.\n\nOur client's daughters were his primary caretakers during this challenging period and were financing his medical needs. Our client wanted to reimburse his daughters for settling his medical bills. However, with only a HDB flat to his name, he could not reimburse them while still alive. As a result, our client decided to Will his HDB flat to his daughters.\n\nWhen our client and his daughters came to our office to sign his Will, he muttered: \"Remember to give the money to your brother.\". Upon hearing that, we immediately stopped him from signing his Will. We then explained to him that if he intended to give his assets to his son, we would make the necessary changes to the Will. The client quickly confirmed that he genuinely wanted to give his assets to his daughters.\n\nHaving sensed that something was amiss, we probed further. After much coaxing, the client finally relented. The client explained that he intended for the HDB flat to be sold upon his death; a portion of the sale proceeds would go to the daughters as reimbursement for the medical bills, and the remainder would be distributed to his son. Both daughters nodded their heads in agreement.\n\nUpon hearing that, we explained to the family that a more appropriate instrument would be a Lasting Power of Attorney.\n\nAs his doctors had suggested hospice care, the client could put the HDB flat up for sale. If he lost his mental capacity during the HDB sale process, his daughters would be able to complete the sale on his behalf. After that, the sale proceeds could be used for hospice care and other medical costs.\n\nThe Lasting Power of Attorney would enable the daughters to manage the father's affairs if the father lost mental capacity, whilst the Will would provide that the assets would be left to the son (as our client initially intended).\n\nOur client and his daughters were very pleased with our proposed solution since:-\n• The daughters would not incur further financial burden nor have the looming accusations of being unfilial for seeking reimbursement for medical costs since the father would be using his monies towards his medical costs;\n• The father was assured that his remaining assets would be given to his son.\n\nSpeak to us for advice on your Estate Planning Matters today!",
